args: That's the last of the fiends.\nGood job, everyone.
Now all that remains is for us to\nmake it to the town on the opposite\nside of these mountains.
*pant* Um, perhaps...we might rest\nfor a little while first?
Yeah, I'm feelin' pretty toasty over here.
I can understand Xiao Lei being tired,\nbut Ranzal, you never get... Goodness!\nYou look like you fell down the mountain!
You ain't lookin' so hot yerself.
Th-that is not... I would never... *pant*
Pray forgive me, Your Highness!\nMy training has clearly been wanting!
Hey, I'm pretty beat myself. A break\nsounds like a good idea for everyone.
Phew! At last, we stop. My poor body\nfeels as if it's made of stone.
I hear ya. Everything I do is makin' me\nfeel like a furry dog on a hot day.
This is odd. That wasn't a particularly\nchallenging battle, and yet we are all\nexhausted.

It's 'cause we fought on top of a mountain.
Fightin' in high places always wears ya
down—I learned that early on in my
old mercenary days.
Oh? Hmm. I wonder what the relationship\nis between one's physical stamina and\nfighting in elevated locations.
Now that you mention it, the closer we\nget to the summit, the less I can feel\nmana in our surroundings.
Perhaps mana is more scarce\nat higher elevations.

Allow me to propose a theory.
Mana surrounds us always, yes?
But if we suppose it grows lesser
in proportion with altitude...
It would mean there is an ＂edge＂ where the\nsky finally ends!
She's talking about her dream to measure\nthe extent of the sky.
Do you really think this might be a clue?
Oh, it's more than a clue—it's an\nactual working hypothesis!
Remember what Cleo said? The higher\nup we go, the greater the reduction\nin mana.
So logically, if we go high enough,\nthe mana should disappear completely.
And I dare say we might find there\na world where neither humans nor\ndragons could survive.
In essence, the edge of the sky!
And finding that is your dream,\nas the prince mentioned earlier?
Is there somethin' GOOD about knowin'\nwhat's at this ＂edge of the sky＂ dealie?
I can't say anything for certain, but...
Ah! Perhaps you could learn something\nabout the weather with this knowledge.
Such as how the clouds are formed,\nwhich way they will move, and the like.
Yes! We might be able to do that!
How wonderful! A working knowledge of\nthe weather would have applications for\na great many things. ...Like laundry!
W-well, we also might NOT be able\nto do that.
Aw, c'mon! Ya can't go playin' with a man's\nemotions like that!
You see, I do not seek to make practical\nUSE of this knowledge.
I simply wish to know the facts\nfor their own sake.
I wish to learn about the edge of the sky,\nand by doing so, the very world itself.
Yeah, this is all way above my pay grade.
And there's nothing wrong with that.
Xiao Lei, you're trying to blaze a brand-\nnew trail—one unknown to everyone.
You're feeling your way along in the dark\nand don't know where the path will lead.
And supposing it does lead somewhere,\nit's perfectly fine to leave the application\nof that information to someone else.
Heh. No surprise he's the one what's able\nto step back and see the big picture.
I must admit, I now find myself most\ncurious about this quest of yours.
Still, I don't even know if the sky DOES\nhave an edge. This is all so very\ntheoretical at this point, after all.
But that's exactly why I need to use my\ncalculations to prove the hypothesis.
I know you can do it.
I'm going to keep thinking it over\nuntil I hit upon a viable method.
Looks like you may have a way to go, then.
Well, to generate an accurate hypothesis,\none needs great amounts of data.

To concretely determine the height of the
sky, we must learn how much mana exists
in general, as well as a great number
of other detailed numbers.
But there's no one who can fly into\nthe sky and begin the investigation,\nso I'm not quite sure how to begin.
Please don't tell me you can fly and\nhave been hiding that this whole time.
Me? No, I'm a ground kind of guy.\nBut we can ask Midgardsormr.
What a fantastic idea! Being a dragon,\nhe will likely also know a good many\nthings about mana.
Perhaps this is a problem that will need\nto be solved by humans and dragons both.
